<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-10-0417 </DOCNO><TEXT>Environmental protection as a political task must be embodied in lawsand implemented in practice. But the citizen's and economic enterprises'specific interests are often opposed to those of society at large. Practicalenvironmental policy attempts by very different means to achieve a consensusamong the groups concerned. This 'guide' describes how the differentinstruments of regluatory law came into being and how they are used,it describes responsibility under criminal law and private liability,the development of economic incentives and endeavours to arrive at voluntaryagreements with polluters, as well as both the effects of public environmentalpolicy and, vice versa, the influences of the public on environmentalpolicy.</TEXT></DOC>